2.1 Import and manipulate data

For data processing:

NOTE: Transects with visibility < 2 m were deleted from the analysis.

NOTE: These analyses include 2015.

NOTES

  • Some rockfishes were recorded in the adult category (eg SECA instead of SECAy) but were small.
  • Set minimum size for rockfishes to 10 cm. fish <= to 10 cm were classified as YOY.
  • Maintained their original designation in SPECIES column. New designation in the group column.

Because there were a lot of zeros for some species, we lumped some species or taxa into higher taxonomic categories. Species higher grouping used in the analyses are:

2.2 Size distributions for select spp

The point of looking at the size distributions is to see if the observed recruitments contributed to age-structure. That is, can we see recruitment pulses in the age structure through time. For the rockfish, the only spp that really makes sense to look at is black rockfish (SEME). They had settlement early on (2016) and are reasonably abundant. We didnt see many adult yellowtail, for example. I also included some plots of EMBI (surfperch) and HEXA (greenling), although these are spp groups not individual species.

Total counts across years by group:

2.4 Seastars

Ive only done Pisaster ochraceaous. we only have data for 2019 for size. Seems strange. However, note that there is a peak of small Pisaster suggesting some recruitment. We did see recruitment of seastar yoy in 2017, so I suppose these could be 2017 stars. I dont know how fast they grow. Seems more likely that they are this years recruits since they are all < 5 cm.
